# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ti-rtos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Texas Instruments embedded processors include TMS320 DSPs, OMAP system-on-a-chip, DaVinci system-on-a-chip, Sitara applications processors, Hercules microcontrollers, Simplelink MCUs (MSP432 and other Wireless connectivity microcontrollers), MSP430 and Tiva/Stellaris microcontrollers.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] It also enables debugging on several subsystems such as Ducati, IVA Accelerator and PRU-ICSS.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Code Composer Studio is primarily designed for embedded project design and low-level (baremetal) JTAG based debugging.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Versions 4.0 to 12.8 are based on the Eclipse open source IDE, which can be easily extended to include support for OS level application debug (Linux, Android, Windows Embedded) and open source compiler suites such as GCC.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Starting with Version 20 in December 2024, CCS is based on the Eclipse Theia platform and IDE.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Early versions included a real time kernel called DSP/BIOS and its later inception SYS/BIOS.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Currently, the successor to these tools, the TI-RTOS embedded tools ecosystem, is available for downloading as a free plugin to Code Composer Studio.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Code Composer Studio was first developed under the name Code Composer by the software company GO DSP, located in Toronto, Canada, which was acquired by Texas Instruments in 1997.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Integration with DSP/BIOS was added to Code Composer, and Code Composer was rebranded as Code Composer Studio.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] CCS releases up until 3.3 were based on a proprietary interface.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] TI developed a new IDE based on the open-source Eclipse, named Code Composer Essentials (CCE), that was designed for the MSP430 line of microcontrollers.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Beginning with release 4.0, all new versions of CCS would also use an interface based upon Eclipse.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Code Composer was originally developed for DSP development and featured graphical visualization tools (XY graphs, FFT magnitude and phase, constellation, raw image visualization) and support for visualizing memory in several numeric formats (decimal, floating-point).
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] In 2015, a cloud computing version of CCS was introduced and is part of the suite TI Cloud Tools, which also hosts Resource Explorer and Pinmux.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] For all releases an annual paid subscription fee was required to grant updates for upcoming major releases.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Historically CCS supported only JTAG debug probes from TI - also called XDS emulators.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] The XDS510-class and the more advanced XDS560-class emulators are supported across all releases, but the new low-cost XDS100-class emulator started to be supported starting with the latest patches to release 3.3.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Releases 4.x added support for an updated design of the existing XDS100-class emulator (called XDS100v2) and, in release 4.2, added support for an updated design of the XDS560-class emulator (called XDS560v2).
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Release 5.2 added support for the new XDS200-class emulators.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Up until release 4.x, CCS supported only XDS emulators.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] With the integration of MSP430 and Stellaris microcontrollers, support was added for their respective JTAG debug probes: MSP-FET430 (both parallel and USB versions) and ICDI.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Release 5.x also saw the introduction of Beta support for J-Link JTAG debug probes from Segger.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Release 6.0.x saw the introduction of the new MSP-FET debug probe for MSP430 devices and the new XDS200-class of debug probes for processors.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Release 6.1.x saw the introduction of the new XDS110-class of debug probes for processors.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] It also saw the migration to full production support for J-Link JTAG debug probes from Segger.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] Release 7.x saw the integration of J-Link JTAG debug probes from Segger directly in the CCS installer.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] It is also the first release to support the standalone version of XDS110.
[src:ti-rtos/code-composer-studio] 64-bit releases do not support Spectrum Digital XDS510USB JTAG debuggers.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] A **digital signal processor** (**DSP**) is a specialized microprocessor chip, with its architecture optimized for the operational needs of digital signal processing.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] DSPs are fabricated on metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) integrated circuit chips.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] They are widely used in audio signal processing, telecommunications, digital image processing, radar, sonar and speech recognition systems, and in common consumer electronic devices such as mobile phones, disk drives and high-definition television (HDTV) products.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The goal of a DSP is usually to measure, filter or compress continuous real-world analog signals.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Most general-purpose microprocessors can also execute digital signal processing algorithms successfully, but may not be able to keep up with such processing continuously in real-time.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Also, dedicated DSPs usually have better power efficiency, thus they are more suitable in portable devices such as mobile phones because of power consumption constraints.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] DSPs often use special memory architectures that are able to fetch multiple data or instructions at the same time.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Digital signal processing (DSP) algorithms typically require a large number of mathematical operations to be performed quickly and repeatedly on a series of data samples.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Signals (perhaps from audio or video sensors) are constantly converted from analog to digital, manipulated digitally, and then converted back to analog form.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Many DSP applications have constraints on latency; that is, for the system to work, the DSP operation must be completed within some fixed time, and deferred (or batch) processing is not viable.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Most general-purpose microprocessors and operating systems can execute DSP algorithms successfully, but are not suitable for use in portable devices such as mobile phones and PDAs because of power efficiency constraints.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] A specialized DSP, however, will tend to provide a lower-cost solution, with better performance, lower latency, and no requirements for specialised cooling or large batteries.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] For example, the SES-12 and SES-14 satellites from operator SES launched in 2018, were both built by Airbus Defence and Space with 25% of capacity using DSP.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The architecture of a DSP is optimized specifically for digital signal processing.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Most also support some of the features of an applications processor or microcontroller, since signal processing is rarely the only task of a system.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Some useful features for optimizing DSP algorithms are outlined below.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Both traditional and DSP-optimized instruction sets are able to compute any arbitrary operation but an operation that might require multiple ARM or x86 instructions to compute might require only one instruction in a DSP-optimized instruction set.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] One implication for software architecture is that hand-optimized assembly-code routines (assembly programs) are commonly packaged into libraries for re-use, instead of relying on advanced compiler technologies to handle essential algorithms.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Even with modern compiler optimizations, hand-optimized assembly code is more efficient, and many common algorithms involved in DSP calculations are hand-written in order to take full advantage of the architectural optimizations.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] DSPs can sometimes rely on supporting code to know about cache hierarchies and the associated delays.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] This is a tradeoff that allows for better performance.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] In addition, extensive use of DMA is employed.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] DSPs frequently use multi-tasking operating systems, but have no support for virtual memory or memory protection.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Operating systems that use virtual memory require more time for context switching among processes, which increases latency.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] In 1976, Richard Wiggins proposed the Speak & Spell concept to Paul Breedlove, Larry Brantingham, and Gene Frantz at Texas Instruments' Dallas research facility.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Two years later in 1978, they produced the first Speak & Spell, with the technological centerpiece being the TMS5100, the industry's first digital signal processor.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] It also set other milestones, being the first chip to use linear predictive coding to perform speech synthesis.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The chip was made possible with a 7 μm PMOS fabrication process.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] In 1978, American Microsystems (AMI) released the S2811.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The AMI S2811 "signal processing peripheral", like many later DSPs, has a hardware multiplier that enables it to do multiply–accumulate operation in a single instruction.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The S2811 was the first integrated circuit chip specifically designed as a DSP, and fabricated using vertical metal oxide semiconductor (VMOS, V-groove MOS), a technology that had previously not been mass-produced.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] It was designed as a microprocessor peripheral, for the Motorola 6800, and it had to be initialized by the host.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The S2811 was not successful in the market.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] In 1979, Intel released the 2920 as an "analog signal processor".
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] It had an on-chip ADC/DAC with an internal signal processor, but it didn't have a hardware multiplier and was not successful in the market.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] In 1980, the first stand-alone complete DSPs, the NEC μPD7720, based on the modified Harvard architecture and AT&T's DSP1 – were presented at the International Solid-State Circuits Conference '80.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Both processors were inspired by the research in public switched telephone network (PSTN) telecommunications.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The μPD7720, introduced for voiceband applications, was one of the most commercially successful early DSPs.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The Altamira DX-1 was another early DSP, utilizing quad integer pipelines with delayed branches and branch prediction.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Another DSP produced by Texas Instruments (TI), the TMS32010, presented in 1983, proved to be an even bigger success.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] It was based on the Harvard architecture, and so had separate instruction and data memory.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] It already had a special instruction set, with instructions like load-and-accumulate or multiply-and-accumulate.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] It could work on 16-bit numbers and needed 390 ns for a multiply–add operation.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] TI is now the market leader in general-purpose DSPs.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] About five years later, the second generation of DSPs began to spread.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] They had 3 memories for storing two operands simultaneously and included hardware to accelerate tight loops; they also had an addressing unit capable of loop-addressing.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Some of them operated on 24-bit variables, and a typical model only required about 21 ns for a MAC.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Members of this generation were, for example, the AT&T DSP16A or the Motorola 56000.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The main improvement in the third generation was the appearance of application-specific units and instructions in the data path, or sometimes as coprocessors.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] These units allowed direct hardware acceleration of very specific but complex mathematical problems, like the Fourier transform or matrix operations.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Some chips, like the Motorola MC68356, even included more than one processor core to work in parallel.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Other DSPs from 1995 are the TI TMS320C541 or the TMS320C80.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The fourth generation is best characterized by the changes in the instruction set and the instruction encoding/decoding.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] SIMD extensions were added, and VLIW and the superscalar architecture appeared.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] As always, the clock speeds have increased; a 3 ns MAC now became possible.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Modern signal processors yield greater performance; this is due in part to both technological and architectural advancements like lower design rules, fast-access two-level cache, (E)DMA circuitry, and a wider bus system.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Not all DSPs provide the same speed and many kinds of signal processors exist, each one of them being better suited for a specific task, ranging in price from about US$1.50 to US$300.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Texas Instruments produces the C6000 series DSPs, which have clock speeds of 1.2 GHz and implement separate instruction and data caches.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] They also have an 8 MiB 2nd level cache and 64 EDMA channels.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The top models are capable of as many as 8000 MIPS (millions of instructions per second), use VLIW (very long instruction word), perform eight operations per clock-cycle and are compatible with a broad range of external peripherals and various buses (PCI/serial/etc).
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] TMS320C6474 chips each have three such DSPs, and the newest generation C6000 chips support floating point as well as fixed point processing.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Freescale produces a multi-core DSP family, the MSC81xx.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The MSC81xx is based on StarCore Architecture processors and the latest MSC8144 DSP combines four programmable SC3400 StarCore DSP cores.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Each SC3400 StarCore DSP core has a clock speed of 1 GHz.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] XMOS produces a multi-core multi-threaded line of processors well suited to DSP operations.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] They come in various speeds ranging from 400 to 1600 MIPS.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The processors have a multi-threaded architecture that allows up to 8 real-time threads per core, meaning that a 4-core device would support up to 32 real-time threads.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Threads communicate with each other through buffered channels that are capable of up to 80 Mbit/s.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] CEVA, Inc. produces and licenses three distinct families of DSPs.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Perhaps the best known and most widely deployed is the CEVA-TeakLite DSP family, a classic memory-based architecture, with 16-bit or 32-bit word-widths and single or dual MACs.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The CEVA-X DSP family offers a combination of VLIW and SIMD architectures, with different members of the family offering dual or quad 16-bit MACs.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The CEVA-XC DSP family targets software-defined radio (SDR) modem designs and leverages a unique combination of VLIW and Vector architectures with 32 16-bit MACs.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Analog Devices produce the SHARC-based DSP and range in performance from 66 MHz/198 MFLOPS (million floating-point operations per second) to 400 MHz/2400 MFLOPS.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Some models support multiple multipliers and ALUs, SIMD instructions and audio processing-specific components and peripherals.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The Blackfin family of embedded digital signal processors combines the features of a DSP with those of a general-purpose processor.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] As a result, these processors can run simple operating systems like μCLinux, Velocity and Nucleus RTOS while operating on real-time data.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The SHARC-based ADSP-210xx provides both delayed branches and non-delayed branches.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] NXP Semiconductors produce DSPs based on TriMedia VLIW technology, optimized for audio and video processing.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] In some products, the DSP core is hidden as a fixed-function block in a SoC, but NXP also provides a range of flexible single-core media processors.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The TriMedia media processors support both fixed-point arithmetic as well as floating-point arithmetic, and have specific instructions to deal with complex filters and entropy coding.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] CSR produces the Quatro family of SoCs that contain one or more custom Imaging DSPs optimized for processing document image data for scanner and copier applications.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Microchip Technology produces the PIC24 based dsPIC line of DSPs.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Introduced in 2004, the dsPIC is designed for applications needing a true DSP as well as a true microcontroller, such as motor control and in power supplies.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The dsPIC runs at up to 40MIPS, and has support for 16-bit fixed-point MAC, bit reverse and modulo addressing, as well as DMA.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Most DSPs use fixed-point arithmetic because, in real-world signal processing, the additional range provided by floating point is not needed, and there is a large speed and cost benefit due to reduced hardware complexity.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Floating-point DSPs may be invaluable in applications where a wide dynamic range is required.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Product developers might also use floating-point DSPs to reduce the cost and complexity of software development in exchange for more expensive hardware, since it is generally easier to implement algorithms in floating point.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Generally, DSPs are dedicated integrated circuits; however, DSP functionality can also be produced by using field-programmable gate array chips (FPGAs).
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Embedded general-purpose RISC processors are becoming increasingly DSP-like in functionality.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] For example, the OMAP3 processors include an ARM Cortex-A8 and C6000 DSP.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] In communications, a new breed of DSPs offering the fusion of both DSP functions and hardware acceleration functions is making its way into the mainstream.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Such Modem processors include ASOCS ModemX and CEVA's XC4000.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] In May 2018, Huarui-2 designed by Nanjing Research Institute of Electronics Technology of China Electronics Technology Group passed acceptance.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] With a processing speed of 0.4 TFLOPS, the chip can achieve better performance than current mainstream DSP chips.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] The design team has begun to create Huarui-3, which has a processing speed in TFLOPS level and support for artificial intelligence.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] An example of such an IC is the Silicon Labs/Skyworks Si4831/35 series, which supports both FM and AM decoding within a single chip.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Many such ICs (including the Si4831/35 above) are suitable for use with – and designed for – externally traditional, mechanically-tuned designs.
[src:ti-rtos/digital-signal-processor] Compared to traditional true analog circuitry, these may exhibit noticeable tuning and audio idiosyncracies (e.g., tuning jumping in discrete steps rather than continuously), particularly with older DSP-based designs.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] A **microcontroller** (**MC**, **uC**, or **μC**) or **microcontroller unit** (**MCU**) is a small computer on a single integrated circuit.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] A microcontroller contains one or more processor cores along with memory and programmable input/output peripherals.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Program memory in the form of NOR flash, OTP ROM, or ferroelectric RAM is also often included on the chip, as well as a small amount of RAM.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers are designed for embedded applications, in contrast to the microprocessors used in personal computers or other general-purpose applications consisting of various discrete chips.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] In modern terminology, a microcontroller is similar to, but less sophisticated than, a system on a chip (SoC).
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] A SoC may include a microcontroller as one of its components but usually integrates it with advanced peripherals like a graphics processing unit (GPU), a Wi-Fi module, or one or more coprocessors.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers are used in automatically controlled products and devices, such as automobile engine control systems, implantable medical devices, remote controls, office machines, appliances, power tools, toys, and other embedded systems.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] By reducing the size and cost compared to a design that uses a separate microprocessor, memory, and input/output devices, microcontrollers make digital control of more devices and processes practical.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Mixed-signal microcontrollers are common, integrating analog components needed to control non-digital electronic systems.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] In the context of the Internet of things, microcontrollers are an economical and popular means of data collection, sensing and actuating the physical world as edge devices.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers may use four-bit words and operate at frequencies as low as 4 kHz for low power consumption (single-digit milliwatts or microwatts).
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] They generally have the ability to retain functionality while waiting for an event such as a button press or other interrupt; power consumption while sleeping (with the CPU clock and most peripherals off) may be just nanowatts, making many of them well suited for long lasting battery applications.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Other microcontrollers may serve performance-critical roles, where they may need to act more like a digital signal processor (DSP), with higher clock speeds and power consumption.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] The first multi-chip microprocessors, the Four-Phase Systems AL1 in 1969 and the Garrett AiResearch MP944 in 1970, were developed with multiple MOS LSI chips.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] The first single-chip microprocessor was the Intel 4004, released on a single MOS LSI chip in 1971.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] It was developed by Federico Faggin, using his silicon-gate MOS technology, along with Intel engineers Marcian Hoff and Stan Mazor, and Busicom engineer Masatoshi Shima.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] It was followed by the 4-bit Intel 4040, the 8-bit Intel 8008, and the 8-bit Intel 8080.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] All of these processors required several external chips to implement a working system, including memory and peripheral interface chips.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] As a result, the total system cost was several hundred (1970s US) dollars, making it impossible to economically computerize small appliances.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] MOS Technology introduced its sub-$100 microprocessors in 1975, the 6501 and 6502.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Their chief aim was to reduce this cost barrier but these microprocessors still required external support, memory, and peripheral chips which kept the total system cost in the hundreds of dollars.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] One book credits TI engineers Gary Boone and Michael Cochran with the successful creation of the first microcontroller in 1971.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] The result of their work was the TMS 1000, which became commercially available in 1974.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] It combined read-only memory, read/write memory, processor and clock on one chip and was targeted at embedded systems.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] During the early-to-mid-1970s, Japanese electronics manufacturers began producing microcontrollers for automobiles, including 4-bit MCUs for in-car entertainment, automatic wipers, electronic locks, and dashboard, and 8-bit MCUs for engine control.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Partly in response to the existence of the single-chip TMS 1000, Intel developed a computer system on a chip optimized for control applications, the Intel 8048, with commercial parts first shipping in 1977.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] It combined RAM and ROM on the same chip with a microprocessor.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Among numerous applications, this chip would eventually find its way into over one billion PC keyboards.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Valenter, stated that the microcontroller was one of the most successful products in the company's history, and he expanded the microcontroller division's budget by over 25%.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Most microcontrollers at this time had concurrent variants.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] One had EPROM program memory, with a transparent quartz window in the lid of the package to allow it to be erased by exposure to ultraviolet light.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] These erasable chips were often used for prototyping.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] The other variant was either a mask-programmed ROM or a PROM variant which was only programmable once.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] For the latter, sometimes the designation *OTP* was used, standing for "one-time programmable".
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] In an OTP microcontroller, the PROM was usually of identical type as the EPROM, but the chip package had no quartz window; because there was no way to expose the EPROM to ultraviolet light, it could not be erased.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Because the erasable versions required ceramic packages with quartz windows, they were significantly more expensive than the OTP versions, which could be made in lower-cost opaque plastic packages.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] For the erasable variants, quartz was required, instead of less expensive glass, for its transparency to ultraviolet light—to which glass is largely opaque—but the main cost differentiator was the ceramic package itself.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] **Piggyback microcontrollers** were also used.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] In 1993, the introduction of EEPROM memory allowed microcontrollers (beginning with the Microchip PIC16C84) to be electrically erased quickly without an expensive package as required for EPROM, allowing both rapid prototyping, and in-system programming.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] (EEPROM technology had been available prior to this time, but the earlier EEPROM was more expensive and less durable, making it unsuitable for low-cost mass-produced microcontrollers.) The same year, Atmel introduced the first microcontroller using Flash memory, a special type of EEPROM.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Other companies rapidly followed suit, with both memory types.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Nowadays microcontrollers are cheap and readily available for hobbyists, with large online communities around certain processors.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] In 2002, about 55% of all CPUs sold in the world were 8-bit microcontrollers and microprocessors.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Over two billion 8-bit microcontrollers were sold in 1997, and according to Semico, over four billion 8-bit microcontrollers were sold in 2006.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] More recently, Semico has claimed the MCU market grew 36.5% in 2010 and 12% in 2011.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] A typical home in a developed country is likely to have only four general-purpose microprocessors but around three dozen microcontrollers.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] A typical mid-range automobile has about 30 microcontrollers.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] They can also be found in many electrical devices such as washing machines, microwave ovens, and telephones.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Cost to manufacture can be under US$0.10 per unit.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Cost has plummeted over time, with the cheapest 8-bit microcontrollers being available for under US$0.03 in 2018, and some 32-bit microcontrollers around US$1 for similar quantities.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] In 2012, following a global crisis—a worst ever annual sales decline and recovery and average sales price year-over-year plunging 17%—the biggest reduction since the 1980s—the average price for a microcontroller was US$0.88 (US$0.69 for 4-/8-bit, US$0.59 for 16-bit, US$1.76 for 32-bit).
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] In 2012, worldwide sales of 8-bit microcontrollers were around US$4 billion, while 4-bit microcontrollers also saw significant sales.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] On 21 June 2018, the "world's smallest computer" was announced by the University of Michigan.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Because they are too small to have conventional radio antennae, they receive and transmit data with visible light.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] A microcontroller can be considered a self-contained system with a processor, memory and peripherals and can be used as an embedded system.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] The majority of microcontrollers in use today are embedded in other machinery, such as automobiles, telephones, appliances, and peripherals for computer systems.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] While some embedded systems are very sophisticated, many have minimal requirements for memory and program length, with no operating system, and low software complexity.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Typical input and output devices include switches, relays, solenoids, LEDs, small or custom liquid-crystal displays, radio frequency devices, and sensors for data such as temperature, humidity, light level etc.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Embedded systems usually have no keyboard, screen, disks, printers, or other recognizable I/O devices of a personal computer, and may lack human interaction devices of any kind.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers must provide real-time (predictable, though not necessarily fast) response to events in the embedded system they are controlling.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Possible interrupt sources are device-dependent and often include events such as an internal timer overflow, completing an analog-to-digital conversion, a logic-level change on an input such as from a button being pressed, and data received on a communication link.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Where power consumption is important as in battery devices, interrupts may also wake a microcontroller from a low-power sleep state where the processor is halted until required to do something by a peripheral event.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Typically microcontroller programs must fit in the available on-chip memory, since it would be costly to provide a system with external, expandable memory.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Compilers and assemblers are used to convert both high-level and assembly language code into a compact machine code for storage in the microcontroller's memory.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Depending on the device, the program memory may be permanent, read-only memory that can only be programmed at the factory, or it may be field-alterable flash or erasable read-only memory.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Manufacturers have often produced special versions of their microcontrollers in order to help the hardware and software development of the target system.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Originally these included EPROM versions that have a "window" on the top of the device through which program memory can be erased by ultraviolet light, ready for reprogramming after a programming ("burn") and test cycle.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Since 1998, EPROM versions are rare and have been replaced by EEPROM and flash, which are easier to use (can be erased electronically) and cheaper to manufacture.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Other versions may be available where the ROM is accessed as an external device rather than as internal memory, however these are becoming rare due to the widespread availability of cheap microcontroller programmers.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] The use of field-programmable devices on a microcontroller may allow field update of the firmware or permit late factory revisions to products that have been assembled but not yet shipped.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Programmable memory also reduces the lead time required for deployment of a new product.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Where hundreds of thousands of identical devices are required, using parts programmed at the time of manufacture can be economical.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] These "mask-programmed" parts have the program laid down in the same way as the logic of the chip, at the same time.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] A customized microcontroller incorporates a block of digital logic that can be personalized for additional processing capability, peripherals and interfaces that are adapted to the requirements of the application.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers usually contain from several to dozens of general purpose input/output pins (GPIO).
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] GPIO pins are software configurable to either an input or an output state.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] When GPIO pins are configured to an input state, they are often used to read sensors or external signals.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Configured to the output state, GPIO pins can drive external devices such as LEDs or motors, often indirectly, through external power electronics.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Many embedded systems need to read sensors that produce analog signals.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] However, because they are built to interpret and process digital data, i.e.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] 1s and 0s, they are not able to do anything with the analog signals that may be sent to it by a device.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] So, an analog-to-digital converter (ADC) is used to convert the incoming data into a form that the processor can recognize.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] A less common feature on some microcontrollers is a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) that allows the processor to output analog signals or voltage levels.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] In addition to the converters, many embedded microprocessors include a variety of timers as well.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] One of the most common types of timers is the programmable interval timer (PIT).
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] A PIT may either count down from some value to zero, or up to the capacity of the count register, overflowing to zero.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Once it reaches zero, it sends an interrupt to the processor indicating that it has finished counting.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] This is useful for devices such as thermostats, which periodically test the temperature around them to see if they need to turn the air conditioner on/off, the heater on/off, etc.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] A dedicated pulse-width modulation (PWM) block makes it possible for the CPU to control power converters, resistive loads, motors, etc., without using many CPU resources in tight timer loops.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] A universal asynchronous receiver/transmitter (UART) block makes it possible to receive and transmit data over a serial line with very little load on the CPU.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Dedicated on-chip hardware also often includes capabilities to communicate with other devices (chips) in digital formats such as Inter-Integrated Circuit (I²C), Serial Peripheral Interface (SPI), Universal Serial Bus (USB), and Ethernet.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers may not implement an external address or data bus as they integrate RAM and non-volatile memory on the same chip as the CPU.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Using fewer pins, the chip can be placed in a much smaller, cheaper package.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Integrating the memory and other peripherals on a single chip and testing them as a unit increases the cost of that chip, but often results in decreased net cost of the embedded system as a whole.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] This integration drastically reduces the number of chips and the amount of wiring and circuit board space that would be needed to produce equivalent systems using separate chips.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Furthermore, on low pin count devices in particular, each pin may interface to several internal peripherals, with the pin function selected by software.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] This allows a part to be used in a wider variety of applications than if pins had dedicated functions.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers have proved to be highly popular in embedded systems since their introduction in the 1970s.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers use a Harvard architecture: separate memory buses for instructions and data, allowing accesses to take place concurrently.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Where a Harvard architecture is used, instruction words for the processor may be a different bit size than the length of internal memory and registers; for example: 12-bit instructions used with 8-bit data registers.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] The decision of which peripheral to integrate is often difficult.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] The microcontroller vendors often trade operating frequencies and system design flexibility against time-to-market requirements from their customers and overall lower system cost.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Manufacturers have to balance the need to minimize the chip size against additional functionality.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontroller architectures vary widely.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Some designs include general-purpose microprocessor cores, with one or more ROM, RAM, or I/O functions integrated onto the package.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Other designs are purpose-built for control applications.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] A microcontroller instruction set usually has many instructions intended for bit manipulation (bit-wise operations) to make control programs more compact.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] For example, a general-purpose processor might require several instructions to test a bit in a register and branch if the bit is set, where a microcontroller could have a single instruction to provide that commonly required function.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers historically have not had math coprocessors, so floating-point arithmetic has been performed by software.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] However, some recent designs do include FPUs and DSP-optimized features.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] An example would be Microchip's PIC32 MIPS-based line.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers were originally programmed only in assembly language, but various high-level programming languages, such as C, Python and JavaScript, are now also in common use to target microcontrollers and embedded systems.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Compilers for general-purpose languages will typically have some restrictions as well as enhancements to better support the unique characteristics of microcontrollers.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers have environments to aid developing certain types of applications.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontroller vendors often make tools freely available to make it easier to adopt their hardware.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers with specialty hardware may require their own non-standard dialects of C, such as SDCC for the 8051, which prevent using standard tools (such as code libraries or static analysis tools) even for code unrelated to hardware features.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Interpreters may also contain nonstandard features, such as MicroPython, although a fork, CircuitPython, has looked to move hardware dependencies to libraries and have the language adhere to a more CPython standard.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Interpreter firmware is also available for some microcontrollers.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] For example, BASIC on the early microcontroller Intel 8052; BASIC and FORTH on the Zilog Z8 as well as some modern devices.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Typically these interpreters support interactive programming.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Simulators are available for some microcontrollers.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] These allow a developer to analyze what the behavior of the microcontroller and their program should be if they were using the actual part.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] A simulator will show the internal processor state and also that of the outputs, as well as allowing input signals to be generated.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] While on the one hand most simulators will be limited from being unable to simulate much other hardware in a system, they can exercise conditions that may otherwise be hard to reproduce at will in the physical implementation, and can be the quickest way to debug and analyze problems.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Recent microcontrollers are often integrated with on-chip debug circuitry that when accessed by an in-circuit emulator (ICE) via JTAG, allow debugging of the firmware with a debugger.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] A real-time ICE may allow viewing and/or manipulating of internal states while running.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] A tracing ICE can record executed program and MCU states before/after a trigger point.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Many others exist, some of which are used in very narrow range of applications or are more like applications processors than microcontrollers.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] The microcontroller market is extremely fragmented, with numerous vendors, technologies, and markets.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Note that many vendors sell or have sold multiple architectures.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] In contrast to general-purpose computers, microcontrollers used in embedded systems often seek to optimize interrupt latency over instruction throughput.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Issues include both reducing the latency, and making it be more predictable (to support real-time control).
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] When an electronic device causes an interrupt, during the context switch the intermediate results (registers) have to be saved before the software responsible for handling the interrupt can run.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] They must also be restored after that interrupt handler is finished.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] If there are more processor registers, this saving and restoring process may take more time, increasing the latency.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Another technique involves spending silicon gates on "shadow registers": One or more duplicate registers used only by the interrupt software, perhaps supporting a dedicated stack.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Lower end microcontrollers tend to support fewer interrupt latency controls than higher end ones.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Two different kinds of memory are commonly used with microcontrollers, a non-volatile memory for storing firmware and a read–write memory for temporary data.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] From the earliest microcontrollers to today, six-transistor SRAM is almost always used as the read/write working memory, with a few more transistors per bit used in the register file.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] In addition to the SRAM, some microcontrollers also have internal EEPROM and/or NVRAM for data storage; and ones that do not have any (such as the BASIC Stamp), or where the internal memory is insufficient, are often connected to an external EEPROM or flash memory chip.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] A few microcontrollers beginning in 2003 have "self-programmable" flash memory.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] The earliest microcontrollers used mask ROM to store firmware.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Later microcontrollers (such as the early versions of the Freescale 68HC11 and early PIC microcontrollers) had EPROM memory, which used a translucent window to allow erasure via UV light, while production versions had no such window, being OTP (one-time-programmable).
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Firmware updates were equivalent to replacing the microcontroller itself, thus many products were not upgradeable.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Motorola MC68HC805 was the first microcontroller to use EEPROM to store the firmware.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] EEPROM microcontrollers became more popular in 1993 when Microchip introduced PIC16C84 and Atmel introduced an 8051-core microcontroller that was first one to use NOR Flash memory to store the firmware.
[src:ti-rtos/microcontroller] Today's microcontrollers almost all use flash memory, with a few models using FRAM and some ultra-low-cost parts still using OTP or mask ROM.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The **MSP430** is a mixed-signal microcontroller family from Texas Instruments, first introduced on 14 February 1992.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Built around a 16-bit CPU, the MSP430 was designed for low power consumption, embedded applications and low cost.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The fundamental feature of the MSP430 is low power consumption.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The first MSP430s (MSP430C3xx) had a consumption around 400 uA/MHz and less than 2 uA in low-power mode with active basic timer and LCD driver.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The more recent MSPs (MSP430FR5xx) have active mode consumption around 100-120 uA/MHz and 500 nA in low-power mode with active RTC.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The consumption of the CPU itself is less than 32 uA/MHz.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The MSP430FR series, which use FRAM instead of a flash, also allow fast writing to a non-volatile memory without additional power requirements.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The MSP430s use up to seven different low-power modes.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The wake-up times differ on the mode and MSP430 generation.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The fastest MSP430-family processors have wake-up times under 1 microsecond.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The MSP430s can run up to 25 MHz, while register-to-register operations take 1 cycle per instruction.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The MSP430 family has more than 550 types, not counted package variants.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] There are microcontrollers with 0.5–512 KB flash or 0.5–256 KB FRAM and up to 66 KB RAM.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Some less usual peripheral options include on-chip operational amplifiers (op-amp) for signal conditioning, 12-bit digital-to-analog converter (DAC), liquid crystal display (LCD) driver, hardware multiplier, USB, and direct memory access (DMA) for ADC results.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] No BSL is included in F20xx, G2xx0, G2xx1, G2xx2, or I20xx family devices.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] There are, however, limits that preclude its use in more complex embedded systems.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The MSP430 does not have an external memory bus, so it is limited to on-chip memory, up to 512 KB flash memory and 66 KB random-access memory (RAM), which may be too small for applications needing large buffers or data tables.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Also, although it has a DMA controller, it is very difficult to use it to move data off the chip due to a lack of a DMA output strobe.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The MSP430 CPU uses a von Neumann architecture, with a single address space for instructions and data.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Memory is byte-addressed, and pairs of bytes are combined little-endian to make 16-bit words.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The processor contains 16 16-bit registers, of which four are dedicated to special purposes: R0 is the program counter, R1 is the stack pointer, R2 is the status register, and R3 is a "constant generator" which reads as zero and ignores writes.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Added address mode encodings using R3 and R2 allow a total of six commonly used constant values (0, 1, 2, 4, 8 and −1) without needing an immediate operand word.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] R4 through R15 are available for general use.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The instruction set is very simple: 27 instructions exist in three categories.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Most instructions occur in .B (8-bit byte) and .W (16-bit word) suffixed versions, depending on the value of a B/W bit: the bit is set to 1 for 8-bit and 0 for 16-bit.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Byte operations to memory affect only the addressed byte, while byte operations to registers clear the most significant byte.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The 10-bit signed jump offset is stored as a word displacement.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The offset is doubled before being added to the PC.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Instructions are 16 bits, followed by up to two 16-bit extension words.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Addressing modes are specified by the 2-bit source addressing mode (As) and the 1-bit destination addressing mode (Ad) fields.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Some special versions can be constructed using R0, and modes other than register direct using R2 (the status register) and R3 (the constant generator) are interpreted specially.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] As Ad is only 1-bit, it can specify only a subset of the addressing modes for As.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Indexed addressing modes add a 16-bit extension word to the instruction.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] If both source and destination are indexed, the source extension word comes first.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] *x* refers to the next extension word in the instruction stream in the table below.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Instructions generally take 1 cycle per word fetched or stored, so instruction times range from 1 cycle for a simple register-register instruction to 6 cycles for an instruction with both source and destination indexed.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The MSP430X extension with 20-bit addressing adds added instructions that can require up to 10 clock cycles.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Setting or clearing a peripheral bit takes two clocks.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] With the 2xx series 2 MCLKs is 125 ns at 16 MHz.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Moves to the program counter are allowed and perform jumps.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Return from subroutine, for example, is implemented as `MOV @SP+,PC`.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] When R0 (PC) or R1 (SP) are used with the autoincrement addressing mode, they are always incremented by two.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Other registers (R4 through R15) are incremented by the operand size, either 1 or 2 bytes.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The status register contains four arithmetic status bits, a global interrupt enable, and four bits that disable various clocks to enter low-power mode.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] When handling an interrupt, the processor saves the status register on the stack and clears the low-power bits.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] If the interrupt handler does not modify the saved status register, returning from the interrupt will then resume the original low-power mode.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Many added instructions are implemented as aliases for forms of the above.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] For example, there is no specific "return from subroutine" instruction, but it is implemented as `MOV @SP+,PC`.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Note that the immediate constants −1 (0xffff), 0, 1, 2, 4 and 8 can be specified in a single-word instruction without needing a separate immediate operand.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The basic MSP430 cannot support more memory (ROM + RAM + peripherals) than its 64K address space.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] In order to support this, an extended form of the MSP430 uses 20-bit registers and a 20-bit address space, allowing up to 1 MB of memory.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] A general prefix word mechanism that can extend any instruction to 20 bits.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The extended instructions include some added abilities, notably multibit shifts and multiregister load/store operations.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] 20-bit operations use the length suffix "A" (for address) instead of .B or .W. .W is still the default.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] In general, shorter operations clear the high-order bits of the destination register.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] All other instructions can have an prefix word added which extends them to 20 bits.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The prefix word contains an added operand size bit, which is combined with the existing B/W bit to specify the operand size.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] One unused size combination exists; indications suggest that it may be used in future for a 32-bit operand size.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The prefix word comes in two formats, and the choice between them depends on the instruction which follows.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] If the instruction has any non-register operands, then the simple form is used, which provides two 4-bit fields to extend any offset or immediate constant in the instruction stream to 20 bits.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] If the instruction is register-to-register, a different extension word is used.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] This includes a "ZC" flag which suppresses carry-in (useful for instructions like DADD which always use the carry bit), and a repeat count.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] A 4-bit field in the extension word encodes either a repeat count (0–15 repetitions in addition to the initial execution), or a register number which contains a 4-bit repeat count.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The following assembler source code is for a subroutine named `memcpy` that copies a block of data words of a given size from one location to another.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The data block is copied one word at a time.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] These must be accessed using 8-bit loads and stores.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] These must be accessed using 16-bit loads and stores.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] 1024 bytes of bootstrap loader ROM (flash parts only).
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Extended RAM on models with more than 2048 bytes of RAM.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] A few models include more than 2048 bytes of RAM; in that case RAM begins at 0x1100.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Also, some recent models bend the 8-bit and 16-bit peripheral rules, allowing 16-bit access to peripherals in the 8-bit peripheral address range.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] There is a new extended version of the architecture (named MSP430X) which allows a 20-bit address space.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] It allows added program ROM beginning at 0x10000.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The '5xx series has a greatly redesigned address space, with the first 4K devoted to peripherals, and up to 16K of RAM.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The MSP430 peripherals are generally easy to use, with (mostly) consistent addresses between models, and no write-only registers (except for the hardware multiplier).
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] If the peripheral is not needed, the pin may be used for general purpose I/O.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The pins are divided into 8-bit groups called "ports", each of which is controlled by a number of 8-bit registers.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] In some cases, the ports are arranged in pairs which can be accessed as 16-bit registers.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The MSP430 family defines 11 I/O ports, P0 through P10, although no chip implements more than 10 of them.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] P0 is only implemented on the '3xx family.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] P7 through P10 are only implemented on the largest members (and highest pin count versions) of the '4xx and '2xx families.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The newest '5xx and '6xx families has P1 through P11, and the control registers are reassigned to provide more port pairs.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Each port is controlled by the following registers.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Ports which do not implement particular features (such as interrupt on state change) do not implement the corresponding registers.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] This is a read-only register, and reflects the current state of the port's pins.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The values written to this read/write register are driven out the corresponding pins when they are configured to output.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Bits written as 1 configure the corresponding pin for output.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Bits written as 0 configure the pin for input.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Bits written as 1 configure the corresponding pin for use by the specialized peripheral.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Bits written as 0 configure the pin for general purpose I/O.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Port 0 ('3xx parts only) is not multiplexed with other peripherals and does not have a P0SEL register.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] on the corresponding I/O pins even when they are configured as inputs.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Bits set in this register enable high current outputs.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Ports 0–2 can produce interrupts when inputs change.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] IFG bit are both set, an interrupt is generated.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] which can be used to handle pin-change interrupts.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Some pins have special purposes either as inputs or outputs.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] (For example, timer pins can be configured as capture inputs or PWM outputs.) In this case, the P*x*DIR bit controls which of the two functions the pin performs when the P*x*SEL bit is set.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] If there is only one special function, then P*x*DIR is generally ignored.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The P*x*IN register is still readable if the P*x*SEL bit is set, but interrupt generation is disabled.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] If P*x*SEL is clear, the special function's input is frozen and disconnected from the external pin.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Also, configuring a pin for general purpose output does *not* disable interrupt generation.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Data transfer controllers and a 16-word conversion-and-control buffer allow the MSP430 to convert and store samples without CPU intervention, minimizing power consumption.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The Analog Pool (A-POOL) module can be configured as an ADC, DAC, comparator, SVS or temperature sensor.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] It allows flexibility for the user to program a series of analog functions with only one setup.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The MSP430's comparator module provides precision slope analog-to-digital conversions.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Monitors external analog signals and provides voltage and resistor value measurement.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The DAC12 module is a 12-bit, voltage-output DAC featuring internal/external reference selection and programmable settling time for optimal power consumption.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] It can be configured in 8- or 12-bit mode.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] When multiple DAC12 modules are present, they may be grouped together for synchronous update operation.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Feature single supply, low current operation with rail-to-rail outputs and programmable settling times.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Software selectable configuration options: unity gain mode, comparator mode, inverting PGA, non-inverting PGA, differential and instrumentation amplifier.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The SD16/SD16_A/SD24_A modules each feature 16-/24-bit sigma–delta A/D converters with an internal 1.2-V reference.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Each converter has up to eight fully differential multiplexed inputs, including a built-in temperature sensor.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The converters are second-order oversampling sigma–delta modulators with selectable oversampling ratios of up to 1024 (SD16_A/SD24_A) or 256 (SD16).
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The BT has two independent 8-bit timers that can be cascaded to form a 16-bit timer/counter.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Both timers can be read and written by software.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The BT is extended to provide an integrated RTC.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] An internal calendar compensates for months with less than 31 days and includes leap-year correction.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] RTC_A/B are 32-bit hardware counter modules that provide clock counters with a calendar, a flexible programmable alarm, and calibration.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The RTC_B includes a switchable battery backup system that provides the ability for the RTC to operate when the primary supply fails.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Timer_A, Timer_B and Timer_D are asynchronous 16-bit timers/counters with up to seven capture/compare registers and various operating modes.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The timers support multiple capture/compares, PWM outputs, and interval timing.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] They also have extensive interrupt capabilities.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The WDT+ performs a controlled system restart after a software problem occurs.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] If the selected time interval expires, a system reset is generated.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] If the watchdog function is not needed in an application, the module can be configured as an interval timer and can generate interrupts at selected time intervals.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The AES accelerator module performs encryption and decryption of 128-bit data with 128-bit keys according to the advanced encryption standard in hardware, and can be configured with user software.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The BOR circuit detects low supply voltages and resets the device by triggering a power-on reset (POR) signal when power is applied or removed.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The MSP430 MCU’s zero-power BOR circuit is continuously turned on, including in all low-power modes.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The DMA controller transfers data from one address to another across the entire address range without CPU intervention.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The DMA increases the throughput of peripheral modules and reduces system power consumption.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The module features up to three independent transfer channels.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Although the MSP430's DMA subsystem is very capable it has several flaws, the most significant of which is the lack of an external transfer strobe.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Although a DMA transfer can be triggered externally, there is no external indication of completion of a transfer.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Consequently DMA to and from external sources is limited to external trigger per byte transfers, rather than full blocks automatically via DMA.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] This can lead to significant complexity (as in requiring extensive hand tweaking of code) when implementing processor to processor or processor to USB communications.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The reference cited uses an obscure timer mode to generate high speed strobes for DMA transfers.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The timers are not flexible enough to easily make up for the lack of an external DMA transfer strobe.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] DMA operations that involve word transfers to byte locations cause truncation to 8 bits rather than conversion to two byte transfers.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] This makes DMA with A/D or D/A 16 bit values less useful than it could be (although it is possible to DMA these values through port A or B on some versions of the MSP 430 using an externally visible trigger per transfer such as a timer output).
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The EEM provides different levels of debug features such as 2-8 hardware breakpoints, complex breakpoints, break when read/write occurs at specified address, and more.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Embedded into all flash-based MSP430 devices.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Some MSP430 models include a memory-mapped hardware multiplier peripheral which performs various 16×16+32→33-bit multiply-accumulate operations.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] This peripheral does not interfere with CPU activities and can be accessed by the DMA.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The MPY on all MSP430F5xx and some MSP430F4xx devices feature up to 32-bit x 32-bit.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The first operand is written to one of four 16-bit registers.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The address written determines the operation performed.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] While the value written can be read back from any of the registers, the register number written to cannot be recovered.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] register, a multiply is performed and the result stored or added to the result registers.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] register is a read-only register that contains the carry out of the addition (0 or 1) in case of an unsigned multiply), or the sign extension of the 32-bit sum (0 or -1) in case of a signed multiply.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] contents to determine the true carry out result (-1, 0, or +1).
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The result is available after three clock cycles of delay, which is the time required to fetch a following instruction and a following index word.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] An explicit delay is only required if using an indirect addressing mode to fetch the result.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The FRAM MPU protects against accidental writes to designated read-only memory segments or execution of code from a constant memory.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The MPU can set any portioning of memory with bit level addressing, making the complete memory accessible for read, write and execute operations in FRAM devices.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The PMM generates a supply voltage for the core logic, and provides several mechanisms for the supervision and monitoring of both the voltage applied to the device and the voltage generated for the core.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] It is integrated with a low-dropout voltage regulator (LDO), brown-out reset (BOR), and a supply voltage supervisor and monitor.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The SVS is a configurable module used to monitor the AVCC supply voltage or an external voltage.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The SVS can be configured to set a flag or generate a power-on reset (POR) when the supply voltage or external voltage drops below a user-selected threshold.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The integrated capacitive touch sense I/O module offers several benefits to touch button and touch slider applications.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The system does not require external components to create the self-oscillation (reducing bill of materials) and the capacitor (that defines the frequency of the self-oscillation) can be connected directly.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] In addition, there is no need for external MUXes to allow multiple pads and each I/O pad can directly serve as a cap sense input.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Control and sequencing is done completely in software.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] MSP430 devices have up to 12 digital I/O ports implemented.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Every I/O pin can be configured as either input or output, and can be individually read or written to.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Ports P1 and P2 have interrupt capability.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] MSP430F2xx, F5xx and some F4xx devices feature built-in, individually configurable pull-up or pull-down resistors.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] GHz transceiver delivers the sensitivity and blocking performance required to achieve successful communication links in any RF environment.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] It also features low current consumption and supports flexible data rates and modulation formats.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The universal synchronous/asynchronous receive/transmit (USART) peripheral interface supports asynchronous RS-232 and synchronous SPI communication with one hardware module.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The MSP430F15x/16x USART modules also support I²C, programmable baud rate, and independent interrupt capability for receive and transmit.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The module supports USB suspend, resume and remote wake-up operations and can be configured for up to eight input and eight output endpoints.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The module includes an integrated physical interface (PHY); a phase-locked loop (PLL) for USB clock generation; and a flexible power-supply system enabling bus-powered and self-powered devices.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The universal serial communication interface (USCI) module features two independent channels that can be used simultaneously.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The asynchronous channel (USCI_A) supports UART mode; SPI mode; pulse shaping for IrDA; and automatic baud-rate detection for LIN communications.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The synchronous channel (USCI_B) supports I²C and SPI modes.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The universal serial interface (USI) module is a synchronous serial communication interface with a data length of up to 16-bits and can support SPI and I²C communication with minimal software.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Available on the MSP430FR4xxx and MSP430FR2xxx series chips, this feature is configured via the SYSCFG register set.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] This peripheral ties into other peripherals (Timers, eUSCI_A) to generate an IR modulated signal on an output pin.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The ESP430CE module performs metering calculations independent of the CPU.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Module has separate SD16, HW multiplier, and the ESP430 embedded processor engine for single-phase energy-metering applications.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The SIF module, a programmable state machine with an analog front end, is used to automatically measure linear or rotational motion with the lowest possible power consumption.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The module features support for different types of LC and resistive sensors and for quadrature encoding.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The LCD/LCD_A controller directly drives LCDs for up to 196 segments.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Supports static, 2-mux, 3-mux, and 4-mux LCDs.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] LCD_A module has integrated charge pump for contrast control.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] LCD_B enables blinking of individual segments with separate blinking memory.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The LCD_E controller comes with the newer MSP430FR4xxx series microcontrollers and directly drives LCDs up to 448 segments.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Segment and Common pins may be reprogrammed to available LCD drive pins.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] This peripheral may be driven in LPM3.5 (RTC running+Main CPU core shutdown low-power mode).
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Texas Instruments provides various hardware experimenter boards that support large (approximately two centimeters square) and small (approximately one millimeter square) MSP430 chips.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] TI also provides software development tools, both directly, and in conjunction with partners (see the full list of compilers, assemblers, and IDEs).
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] One such toolchain is the IAR C/C++ compiler and *Integrated development environment*, or IDE.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] A Kickstart edition can be downloaded for free from TI or IAR; it is limited to 8 KB of C/C++ code in the compiler and debugger (assembly language programs of any size can be developed and debugged with this free toolchain).
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] TI also combines a version of its own compiler and tools with its Eclipse-based Code Composer Studio IDE (CCS).
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] It sells full-featured versions, and offers a free version for download which has a code size limit of 16 KB.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] CCS supports in-circuit emulators, and includes a simulator and other tools; it can also work with other processors sold by TI.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The open source community produces a freely available software development toolset based on the GNU toolset.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] TI consulted with RedHat to provide official support for the MSP430 architecture to the GNU Compiler Collection C/C++ compiler.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] This msp430-elf-gcc compiler is supported by TI's Code Composer Studio version 6.0 and higher.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] There is a very early llvm-msp430 project, which may eventually provide better support for MSP430 in LLVM.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Other commercial development tool sets, which include editor, compiler, linker, assembler, debugger and in some cases code wizards, are available.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] VisSim, a block diagram language for model based development, generates efficient fixed point C-Code directly from the diagram.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] VisSim generated code for a closed loop ADC+PWM based PID control on the F2013 compiles to less than 1 KB flash and 100 bytes RAM.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] VisSim has on-chip peripheral blocks for the entire MSP430 family I²C, ADC, SD16, PWM.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The MSP430F2013 and its siblings are set apart by the fact that (except for the MSP430G2 Value Line) it is the only MSP430 part that is available in a dual in-line package (DIP).
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Other variants in this family are only available in various surface-mount packages.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] TI has gone to some trouble to support the eZ430 development platform by making the raw chips easy for hobbyists to use in prototypes.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] TI has tackled the low-budget problem by offering a very small experimenter board, the *eZ430-F2013*, on a USB stick (now obsolete).
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] This made it easy for designers to choose the MSP430 chip for inexpensive development platforms that can be used with a computer.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The eZ430-F2013 contains an MSP430F2013 microcontroller on a detachable prototyping board, and accompanying CD with development software.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] It is helpful for schools, hobbyists and garage inventors.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] It is also welcomed by engineers in large companies prototyping projects with capital budget problems.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Texas Instruments released the MSP430 LaunchPad in July 2010 at a cost of $4.30.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The MSP430 LaunchPad has an onboard flash emulator, USB, 2 programmable LEDs, and 1 programmable push button.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] As an addition to experimentation with the LaunchPad a shield board is available.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] All three of these LaunchPads include an eZ-FET JTAG debugger with backchannel UART capable of 1 Mbit/s speeds.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] MSP-EXP430FR5969, MSP-EXP430FR4133) include EnergyTrace, a feature supported by TI's Code Composer Studio IDE for monitoring and analyzing power consumption.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] In common with other microcontroller vendors, TI has developed a two-wire debugging interface found on some of their MSP430 parts that can replace the larger JTAG interface.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The eZ430 Development Tool contains a full USB-connected flash emulation tool (FET) for this new two-wire protocol, named *Spy-Bi-Wire* by TI.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Spy-Bi-Wire was initially introduced on only the smallest devices in the 'F2xx family with limited number of I/O pins, such as the MSP430F20xx, MSP430F21x2, and MSP430F22x2.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The support for Spy-Bi-Wire has been expanded with the introduction of the latest '5xx family, where all devices have support Spy-Bi-Wire interface in addition to JTAG.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The advantage of the Spy-Bi-Wire protocol is that it uses only two communication lines, one of which is the dedicated _RESET line.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] The JTAG interface on the lower pin count MSP430 parts is multiplexed with general purpose I/O lines.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] This makes it relatively difficult to debug circuits built around the small, low-I/O-budget chips, since the full 4-pin JTAG hardware will conflict with anything else connected to those I/O lines.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] This problem is alleviated with the Spy-Bi-Wire-capable chips, which are still compatible with the normal JTAG interface for backwards compatibility with the old development tools.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] JTAG debugging and flash programming tools based on OpenOCD and widely used in the ARM architecture community are not available for the MSP430.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] Programming tools specially designed for the MSP430 are marginally less expensive than JTAG interfaces that use OpenOCD.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p01] However, should it be discovered mid-project that more MIPS, more memory, and more I/O peripherals are needed, those tools will not transfer to a processor from another vendor.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] Six general generations of MSP430 processors exist.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] In order of development, they are: '3xx generation, '1xx generation, '4xx generation, '2xx generation, '5xx generation, and '6xx generation.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] The digit after the generation identifies the model (generally higher model numbers are larger and more capable), the third digit identifies the amount of memory included, and the fourth, if present, identifies a minor model variant.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] The most common variation is a different on-chip analog-to-digital converter.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] The 3xx and 1xx generations are limited to a 16-bit address space.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] In the later generations this was expanded to include '430X' instructions that allow a 20-bit address space.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] As happened with other processor architectures (e.g. the processor of the PDP-11), extending the addressing range beyond the 16-bit word size introduced some peculiarities and inefficiencies for programs larger than 64 KB.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] In the following list, it helps to think of the typical 200 mA·Hr capacity of a CR2032 lithium coin cell as 200,000 μA·Hr, or 22.8 μA·year.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] Thus, considering only the CPU draw, such a battery could supply a 0.7 μA current draw for 32 years.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] The significance of the *RAM retention* vs the *real-time clock mode* is that in real time clock mode the CPU can go to sleep with a clock running which will wake it up at a specified future time.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] In RAM retention mode, some external signal is required to wake it, e.g., input/output (I/O) pin signal or SPI slave receive interrupt.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] The MSP430x1xx Series is the first generation with flash memory.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] They are generally more capable than the '3xx generation, but without an embedded LCD controller.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] These flash- or ROM-based ultra-low-power MCUs offer 8 MIPS, 1.8–3.6 V operation, up to 60 KB flash, and a wide range of analog and digital peripherals.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] The MSP430F2xx Series are similar to the '1xx generation, but operate at even lower power, support up to 16 MHz operation, and have a more accurate (±2%) on-chip clock that makes it easier to operate without an external crystal.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] These flash-based ultra-low power devices offer 1.8–3.6 V operations.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] It includes the very-low power oscillator (VLO), internal pull-up/pull-down resistors, and low-pin count options.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] The MSP430G2xx Value Series features flash-based Ultra-Low Power MCUs up to 16 MIPS with 1.8–3.6 V operation.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] It includes the Very-Low power Oscillator (VLO), internal pull-up/pull-down resistors, and low-pin count options at lower prices than the MSP430F2xx series.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] The MSP430x3xx Series is the oldest generation, released between 1995 and 1998.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] The MSP430 was designed as a successor to TSS400 for battery-powered metering instruments.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] All MSP430x3xx had an embedded LCD controller and also a digital controlled oscillator (DCO) with frequency-locked loop (FLL) which provided a stable system clock (1 to 4 MHz) using a low-frequency crystal (32 kHz).
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] This generation does not support EEPROM memory, only mask ROM and UV-eraseable and one-time programmable EPROM.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] Later generations provide only flash memory and mask ROM options.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] These devices offer 2.5–5.5 V operation, up to 32 KB ROM.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] The MSP430x4xx Series are similar to the '1xx generation, but include an integrated LCD controller, and are larger and often more capable.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] These flash or ROM based devices offers 8–16 MIPS at 1.8–3.6 V operation, with FLL, and SVS.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] Ideal for low power metering and medical applications.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] The MSP430x5xx Series are able to run up to 25 MHz, have up to 512 KB flash memory and up to 66 KB RAM.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] This flash-based family features low active power consumption with up to 25 MIPS at 1.8–3.6 V operation (165 uA/MIPS).
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] Includes an innovative power management module for optimal power consumption and integrated USB.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] The MSP430x6xx Series are able to run up to 25 MHz, have up to 512 KB flash memory and up to 66 KB RAM.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] Many 6xx series devices are pin-compatible with an analogous 5xx series device except that the 6xx device adds USB support.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] The RF SoC (CC430) Series provides tight integration between the microcontroller core, peripherals, software, and RF transceiver.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] Features <1 GHz RF transceiver, with 1.8 V–3.6 V operation.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] Programming using Arduino integrated development environment (IDE) is possible via the panStamp API.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] The FRAM Series from Texas Instruments provides unified memory with dynamic partitioning and memory write speeds 100 times faster than flash.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] FRAM is also capable of zero power state retention in all power modes, which means that writes are guaranteed, even in the event of a power loss.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] With a write endurance of over 100 trillion cycles, EEPROM is no longer required.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] Active power consumption at less than 100 μA/MHz.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] The Low Voltage Series include the MSP430C09x and MSP430L092 parts, capable of running at 0.9 V.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] These 2 series of low voltage 16-bit microcontrollers have configurations with two 16-bit timers, an 8-bit analog-to-digital (A/D) converter, an 8-bit digital-to-analog (D/A) converter, and up to 11 I/O pins.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] More families within MSP430 include Fixed Function, Automotive, and Extended Temp parts.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] Fixed Function: The MSP430BQ1010 16-bit microcontroller is an advanced fixed-function device that forms the control and communications unit on the receiver side for wireless power transfer in portable applications.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] MSP430BQ1010 complies with the Wireless Power Consortium (WPC) specification.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] For more information, see Contactless Power.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] Automotive: Automotive MSP430 microcontrollers (MCUs) from Texas Instruments (TI) are 16-bit, RISC-based, mixed-signal processors that are AEC-Q100 qualified and suitable for automotive applications in environments up to 105 °C ambient temperature.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] LIN compliant drivers for the MSP430 MCU provided by IHR GmbH.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] Extended Temp: MSP430 devices are very popular in harsh environments such as industrial sensing for their low power consumption and innovative analog integration.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] Some harsh environment applications include transportation/automotive, renewable energy, military/space/avionics, mineral exploration, industrial, and safety & security.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] Note that when the flash size is over 64K words (128 KBytes), instruction addresses can no longer be encoded in just two bytes.
[src:ti-rtos/msp430-p02] This change in pointer size causes some incompatibilities with previous parts.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A **real-time operating system** (**RTOS**) is an operating system (OS) for real-time computing applications that processes data and events that have critically defined time constraints.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS mainly targets resource constrained devices like microcontrollers.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] It is distinct from a time-sharing operating system, such as Unix, which manages the sharing of system resources with a scheduler, data buffers, or fixed task prioritization in multitasking or multiprogramming environments.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] All operations must verifiably complete within given time and resource constraints or else the RTOS will fail safe.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Real-time operating systems are event-driven and preemptive, meaning the OS can monitor the relevant priority of competing tasks, and make changes to the task priority.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A key characteristic of an RTOS is the level of its consistency concerning the amount of time it takes to accept and complete an application's task; the variability is "jitter".
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The chief design goal is not high throughput, but rather a guarantee of a soft or hard performance category.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS that can usually or generally meet a deadline is a soft real-time OS, but if it can meet a deadline deterministically it is a hard real-time OS.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS has an advanced algorithm for scheduling.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Scheduler flexibility enables a wider, computer-system orchestration of process priorities, but a real-time OS is more frequently dedicated to a narrow set of applications.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Key factors in a real-time OS are minimal interrupt latency and minimal thread switching latency; a real-time OS is valued more for how quickly or how predictably it can respond than for the amount of work it can perform in a given period of time.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Time sharing designs switch tasks more often than strictly needed, but give smoother multitasking, giving the illusion that a process or user has sole use of a machine.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Early CPU designs needed many cycles to switch tasks during which the CPU could do nothing else useful.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Because switching took so long, early OSes tried to minimize wasting CPU time by avoiding unnecessary task switching.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Blocked (waiting for an event, I/O for example).
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Most tasks are blocked or ready most of the time because generally only one task can run at a time per CPU core.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The number of items in the ready queue can vary greatly, depending on the number of tasks the system needs to perform and the type of scheduler that the system uses.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] On simpler non-preemptive but still multitasking systems, a task has to give up its time on the CPU to other tasks, which can cause the ready queue to have a greater number of overall tasks in the ready to be executed state (resource starvation).
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] If there are never more than a few tasks on the ready list, then a doubly linked list of ready tasks is likely optimal.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] If the ready list usually contains only a few tasks but occasionally contains more, then the list should be sorted by priority, so that finding the highest priority task to run does not require traversing the list.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Instead, inserting a task requires walking the list.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] During this search, preemption should not be inhibited.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Long critical sections should be divided into smaller pieces.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] If an interrupt occurs that makes a high priority task ready during the insertion of a low priority task, that high priority task can be inserted and run immediately before the low priority task is inserted.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The critical response time, sometimes called the flyback time, is the time it takes to queue a new ready task and restore the state of the highest priority task to running.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In a well-designed RTOS, readying a new task will take 3 to 20 instructions per ready-queue entry, and restoration of the highest-priority ready task will take 5 to 30 instructions.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In advanced systems, real-time tasks share computing resources with many non-real-time tasks, and the ready list can be arbitrarily long.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In such systems, a scheduler ready list implemented as a linked list would be inadequate.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A multitasking operating system like Unix is poor at real-time tasks.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The scheduler gives the highest priority to jobs with the lowest demand on the computer, so there is no way to ensure that a time-critical job will have access to enough resources.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Multitasking systems must manage sharing data and hardware resources among multiple tasks.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] It is usually unsafe for two tasks to access the same specific data or hardware resource simultaneously.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] General-purpose operating systems usually do not allow user programs to mask (disable) interrupts, because the user program could control the CPU for as long as it is made to.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Some modern CPUs do not allow user mode code to disable interrupts as such control is considered a key operating system resource.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Many embedded systems and RTOSs, however, allow the application itself to run in kernel mode for greater system call efficiency and also to permit the application to have greater control of the operating environment without requiring OS intervention.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] On single-processor systems, an application running in kernel mode and masking interrupts is the lowest overhead method to prevent simultaneous access to a shared resource.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] While interrupts are masked and the current task does not make a blocking OS call, the current task has *exclusive* use of the CPU since no other task or interrupt can take control, so the critical section is protected.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] When the task exits its critical section, it must unmask interrupts; pending interrupts, if any, will then execute.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Temporarily masking interrupts should only be done when the longest path through the critical section is shorter than the desired maximum interrupt latency.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Typically this method of protection is used only when the critical section is just a few instructions and contains no loops.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] This method is ideal for protecting hardware bit-mapped registers when the bits are controlled by different tasks.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] When the shared resource must be reserved without blocking all other tasks (such as waiting for Flash memory to be written), it is better to use mechanisms also available on general-purpose operating systems, such as a mutex and OS-supervised interprocess messaging.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Such mechanisms involve system calls, and usually invoke the OS's dispatcher code on exit, so they typically take hundreds of CPU instructions to execute, while masking interrupts may take as few as one instruction on some processors.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A (non-recursive) mutex is either **locked** or unlocked.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] When a task has locked the mutex, all other tasks must wait for the mutex to be unlocked by its *owner* - the original thread.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A task may set a timeout on its wait for a mutex.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] There are several well-known problems with mutex based designs such as priority inversion and deadlocks.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In priority inversion a high priority task waits because a low priority task has a mutex, but the lower priority task is not given CPU time to finish its work.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A typical solution is to have the task that owns a mutex 'inherit' the priority of the highest waiting task.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] But this simple approach gets more complex when there are multiple levels of waiting: task *A* waits for a mutex locked by task *B*, which waits for a mutex locked by task *C*.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Handling multiple levels of inheritance causes other code to run in high priority context and thus can cause starvation of medium-priority threads.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In a deadlock, two or more tasks lock mutex without timeouts and then wait forever for the other task's mutex, creating a cyclic dependency.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The simplest deadlock scenario occurs when two tasks alternately lock two mutex, but in the opposite order.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Deadlock is prevented by careful design.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The other approach to resource sharing is for tasks to send messages in an organized message passing scheme.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In this paradigm, the resource is managed directly by only one task.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] When another task wants to interrogate or manipulate the resource, it sends a message to the managing task.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Although their real-time behavior is less crisp than semaphore systems, simple message-based systems avoid most protocol deadlock hazards, and are generally better-behaved than semaphore systems.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] However, problems like those of semaphores are possible.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Priority inversion can occur when a task is working on a low-priority message and ignores a higher-priority message (or a message originating indirectly from a high priority task) in its incoming message queue.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Protocol deadlocks can occur when two or more tasks wait for each other to send response messages.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Since an interrupt handler blocks the highest priority task from running, and since real-time operating systems are designed to keep thread latency to a minimum, interrupt handlers are typically kept as short as possible.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The interrupt handler defers all interaction with the hardware if possible; typically all that is necessary is to acknowledge or disable the interrupt (so that it won't occur again when the interrupt handler returns) and notify a task that work needs to be done.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] This can be done by unblocking a driver task through releasing a semaphore, setting a flag or sending a message.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A scheduler often provides the ability to unblock a task from interrupt handler context.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] An OS maintains catalogues of objects it manages such as threads, mutexes, memory, and so on.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Updates to this catalogue must be strictly controlled.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, it can be problematic when an interrupt handler calls an OS function while the application is in the act of also doing so.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The OS function called from an interrupt handler could find the object database to be in an inconsistent state because of the application's update.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] There are two major approaches to deal with this problem: the unified architecture and the segmented architecture.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] RTOSs implementing the unified architecture solve the problem by simply disabling interrupts while the internal catalogue is updated.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The downside of this is that interrupt latency increases, potentially losing interrupts.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The segmented architecture does not make direct OS calls but delegates the OS related work to a separate handler.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] This handler runs at a higher priority than any thread but lower than the interrupt handlers.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The advantage of this architecture is that it adds very few cycles to interrupt latency.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] As a result, OSes which implement the segmented architecture are more predictable and can deal with higher interrupt rates compared to the unified architecture.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Similarly, the System Management Mode on x86 compatible hardware can take a lot of time before it returns control to the operating system.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Memory allocation is more critical in a real-time operating system than in other operating systems.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] First, for stability there cannot be memory leaks (memory that is allocated but not freed after use).
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The device should work indefinitely, without ever needing a reboot.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, dynamic memory allocation is frowned upon.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Whenever possible, all required memory allocation is specified statically at compile time.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Another reason to avoid dynamic memory allocation is memory fragmentation.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] With frequent allocation and releasing of small chunks of memory, a situation may occur where available memory is divided into several sections and the RTOS cannot allocate a large enough continuous block of memory, although there is enough free memory.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Secondly, speed of allocation is important.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A standard memory allocation scheme scans a linked list of indeterminate length to find a suitable free memory block, which is unacceptable in a RTOS since memory allocation has to occur within a certain amount of time.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Because mechanical disks have much longer and more unpredictable response times, swapping to disk files is not used for the same reasons as RAM allocation discussed above.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The simple fixed-size-blocks algorithm works quite well for simple embedded systems because of its low overhead.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] While all RTOSes are able to run on microcontrollers they have ports for, some RTOSes like Zephyr are capable of abstracting even further a number of device drivers like External Flash, I2C devices or internal peripherals like UART commands and sleep modes.
[src:ti-rtos/real-time-operating-system] This helps offload the need for a developer to create drivers and instead a set of APIs are given for unsupported drivers to be ported over while supported ones are ready for use within the application code.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Texas Instruments emerged in 1951 from the reorganization of Geophysical Service Incorporated, a company founded in 1930 that manufactured equipment for the seismic industry and defense electronics.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI produced the world's first commercial silicon transistor in 1954, and the same year designed and manufactured the first transistor radio.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Jack Kilby invented the integrated circuit in 1958 while working at TI's Central Research Labs.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI also invented the handheld calculator in 1967 and introduced the first single-chip microcontroller in 1970, combining all the elements of computing onto a single chip.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1987, TI invented the digital light processing device (also known as the DLP chip), which serves as the foundation for the company's DLP technology and DLP Cinema.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI released the popular TI-81 calculator in 1990, which made it a leader in the graphing calculator industry.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Its defense business was sold to Raytheon Company in 1997, allowing TI to strengthen its focus on digital solutions.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] After the acquisition of National Semiconductor in 2011, the company had a combined portfolio of 45,000 analog products and customer design tools.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Texas Instruments was founded by Cecil H.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Erik Jonsson, Eugene McDermott, and Patrick E.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] McDermott was one of the original founders of Geophysical Service Inc.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] McDermott, Green, and Jonsson were GSI employees who purchased the company in 1941.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In November 1945, Patrick Haggerty was hired as general manager of the Laboratory and Manufacturing (L&M) division, which focused on electronic equipment.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] By 1951, the L&M division, with its defense contracts, was growing faster than GSI's geophysical division.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The company was reorganized and initially renamed General Instruments Inc.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Because a firm named General Instrument already existed, the company was renamed Texas Instruments that same year.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] From 1956 to 1961, Fred Agnich of Dallas, later a Republican member of the Texas House of Representatives, served as president of Texas Instruments.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Geophysical Service, Inc. became a subsidiary of Texas Instruments.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Early in 1988, most of GSI was sold to the Halliburton Company.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Clarence Karcher and Eugene McDermott founded Geophysical Service, an early provider of seismic exploration services to the petroleum industry.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1939, the company reorganized as Coronado Corp, an oil company with Geophysical Service Inc (GSI), now as a subsidiary.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] On December 6, 1941, McDermott along with three other GSI employees, J.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] During World War II, GSI expanded its services to include electronics for the U.S.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1951, the company changed its name to Texas Instruments, spun off to build seismographs for oil explorations and with GSI becoming a wholly owned subsidiary of the new company.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] An early success came for TI-GSI in 1965, when GSI was able (under a Top Secret government contract) to monitor the Soviet Union's underground nuclear weapons testing under the ocean in Vela Uniform, a subset of Project Vela, to verify compliance of the Partial Nuclear Test Ban Treaty.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Texas Instruments also continued to manufacture equipment for use in the seismic industry, and GSI continued to provide seismic services.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] After selling (and repurchasing) GSI, TI finally sold the company to Halliburton in 1988, after which sale GSI ceased to exist as a separate entity.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In early 1952, Texas Instruments purchased a patent license from Western Electric, the manufacturing arm of AT&T, to produce germanium transistors for US$25,000, beginning production by the end of the year.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Haggerty brought Gordon Teal to the company due to his expertise in growing semiconductor crystals while at Bell Telephone Laboratories.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Teal's first assignment was to direct TI's research laboratory.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] At the end of 1952, Texas Instruments announced that it had expanded to 2,000 employees and $17 million in sales.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Among his new hires was Willis Adcock, who joined TI early in 1953.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Adcock, who like Teal was a physical chemist, began leading a small research group focused on the task of fabricating grown-junction, silicon, single-crystal, small-signal transistors.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Adcock later became the first TI Principal Fellow.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In January 1954, Morris Tanenbaum at Bell Telephone Laboratories created the first workable silicon transistor.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] This work was reported in the spring of 1954, at the IRE off-the-record conference on solid-state devices, and was later published in the *Journal of Applied Physics*.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Working independently in April 1954, Gordon Teal at TI created the first commercial silicon transistor and tested it on April 14, 1954.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] On May 10, 1954, at the Institute of Radio Engineers National Conference on Airborne Electronics in Dayton, Ohio, Teal presented a paper: "Some Recent Developments in Silicon and Germanium Materials and Devices".
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1954, Texas Instruments designed and manufactured the first transistor radio.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The Regency TR-1 used germanium transistors, as silicon transistors were much more expensive at the time.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] This was an effort by Haggerty to increase market demand for transistors.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Jack Kilby, an employee at TI, invented the integrated circuit in 1958.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Kilby recorded his initial ideas concerning the integrated circuit in July 1958 and successfully demonstrated the world's first working integrated circuit on September 12, 1958.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Six months later, Robert Noyce of Fairchild Semiconductor (who went on to co-found Intel) independently developed the integrated circuit with integrated interconnect and is also considered an inventor of the integrated circuit.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1969, Kilby was awarded the National Medal of Science, and in 1982 he was inducted into the National Inventor's Hall of Fame.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Kilby also won the 2000 Nobel Prize in Physics for his part of the invention of the integrated circuit.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Noyce's chip, made at Fairchild, was made of silicon, while Kilby's chip was made of germanium.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 2008, TI named its new development laboratory "Kilby Labs" after Jack Kilby.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The 7400 series of transistor-transistor logic chips, developed by Texas Instruments in the 1960s, popularized the use of integrated circuits in computer logic.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The military-grade version of this was the 5400 series.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Texas Instruments invented the hand-held calculator (a prototype called "Cal Tech") in 1967 and the single-chip microcomputer in 1971, was assigned the first patent on a single-chip microprocessor (invented by Gary Boone) on September 4, 1973.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] This was disputed by Gilbert Hyatt, formerly of the Micro Computer Company, in August 1990, when he was awarded a patent superseding TI's.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] This was overturned on June 19, 1996, in favor of TI (note: Intel is usually given credit with Texas Instruments for the almost-simultaneous invention of the microprocessor).
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1978, Texas Instruments introduced the first single-chip linear predictive coding speech synthesizer.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1976, TI began a feasibility study of memory-intensive applications for bubble memory then being developed.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] They soon focused on speech applications.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] This resulted in the development of the TMC0280 one-chip linear predictive coding speech synthesizer, which was the first time a single silicon chip had electronically replicated the human voice.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] This was used in several TI commercial products beginning with Speak & Spell, which was introduced at the Summer Consumer Electronics Show in June 1978.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 2001, TI left the speech synthesis business, selling it to Sensory Inc. of Santa Clara, California.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In May 1954, Texas Instruments designed and built a prototype of the world's first transistor radio, and, through a partnership with Industrial Development Engineering Associates of Indianapolis, Indiana, the 100% solid-state radio was sold to the public beginning in October of that year.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In the 1960s, company president Pat Haggerty had a team that included Jack Kilby to work on a handheld calculator project.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Kilby and two other colleagues created the Cal-Tech, a three-pound battery-powered calculator that could do basic math and fit six-digit numbers on its display.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] This 4.25 x 6.15 x 1.75 inch calculator's processor would originate the vast majority of Texas Instruments’ revenue.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1973, the handheld calculator SR-10 (named after slide rule) and in 1974, the handheld scientific calculator SR-50 were issued by TI.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Both had red LED-segments numeric displays.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The optical design of the SR-50 is somewhat similar to the HP-35 edited by Hewlett-Packard before in early 1972, but buttons for the operations "+", "–", ... are in the right of the number block and the decimal point lies between two neighboring digits.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI remained active in the consumer electronics market throughout the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Early on, this also included two digital clock models – one for desk and the other a bedside alarm.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] From this sprang what became the Time Products Division, which made LED watches.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Though these LED watches enjoyed early commercial success due to excellent quality, it was short-lived due to poor battery life.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] LEDs were replaced with LCD watches for a short time, but these could not compete due to styling issues, excessive model variety, and price points.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The watches were manufactured in Dallas and then Lubbock, Texas.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Several spin-offs of the Speak & Spell, such as the Speak & Read and Speak & Math, were introduced soon thereafter.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1979, TI entered the home computer market with the TI-99/4, a competitor to computers such as the Apple II, TRS-80, and the later Atari 400/800 and VIC-20.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] By late 1982, TI was dominating the U.S. home computer market, shipping 5,000 computers a day from its factory in Lubbock.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] It discontinued the TI-99/4A (1981), the sequel to the 99/4, in late 1983 amid an intense price war waged primarily against Commodore.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] At the 1983 Winter CES, TI showed models 99/2 and the Compact Computer 40, the latter aimed at professional users.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The TI Professional (1983) ultimately joined the ranks of the many unsuccessful MS-DOS and x86-based—but non-compatible—competitors to the IBM PC (the founders of Compaq, an early leader in PC compatibles, all came from TI).
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The company for years successfully made and sold PC-compatible laptops before withdrawing from the market and selling its product line to Acer in 1997.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI entered the defense electronics market in 1942 with submarine detection equipment, based on the seismic exploration technology previously developed for the oil industry.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The division responsible for these products was known at different times as the Laboratory & Manufacturing Division, the Apparatus Division, the Equipment Group, and the Defense Systems & Electronics Group (DSEG).
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] During the early 1980s, TI instituted a quality program which included Juran training, as well as promoting statistical process control, Taguchi methods, and Design for Six Sigma.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In the late 1980s, the company, along with Eastman Kodak and Allied Signal, began involvement with Motorola, institutionalizing Motorola's Six Sigma methodology.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Motorola, which originally developed the Six Sigma methodology, began this work in 1982.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1992, the DSEG division of Texas Instruments' quality-improvement efforts were rewarded by winning the Malcolm Baldrige National Quality Award for manufacturing.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI developed the AAA-4 infrared search and track device in the late 1950s and early 1960s for the F-4B Phantom for passive scanning of jet-engine emissions, but it possessed limited capabilities and was eliminated on F-4Ds and later models.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1956, TI began research on infrared technology that led to several line scanner contracts, with the addition of a second scan mirror, to the invention of the first forward-looking infrared (FLIR) in 1963, with production beginning in 1966.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1972, TI invented the common module FLIR concept, greatly reducing cost and allowing reuse of common components.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI went on to produce side-looking radar systems, the first terrain-following radar and surveillance radar systems for both the military and the FAA.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI demonstrated the first solid-state radar called Molecular Electronics for Radar Applications (MERA).
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1976, TI developed a microwave landing system prototype.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1984, TI developed the first inverse synthetic-aperture radar.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The first single-chip gallium arsenide radar module was developed.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1991, the military microwave integrated circuit program was initiated, as a joint effort with Raytheon.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1961, TI won the guidance and control system contract for the defense suppression AGM-45 Shrike anti-radiation missile.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] This led later to the prime on the high-speed antiradiation missile (AGM-88 HARM) development contract in 1974 and production in 1981.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1964, TI began developing the first laser guidance system for precision-guided munitions, leading to the Paveway series of laser-guided bombs (LGBs).
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1969, TI won the Harpoon (missile) Seeker contract.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1986, TI won the Army FGM-148 Javelin fire-and-forget man-portable antitank guided missile in a joint venture with Martin Marietta.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1991, TI was awarded the contract for the AGM-154 Joint Standoff Weapon.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI's research and development of military temperature-range silicon transistors and integrated circuits (ICs) led to TI winning contracts for the first IC-based computer for the U.S.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Air Force in 1961 (the so-called Molecular Electronic Computer) and for ICs for the Minuteman Missile the following year.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1968, TI developed the data systems for the Mariner Program.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1991, TI won the F-22 Radar and Computer development contract.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] As the defense industry consolidated, TI sold its defense business to the Raytheon Company in 1997 for $2.95 billion.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The Department of Justice required that Raytheon divest the TI Monolithic Microwave Integrated Circuit (MMIC) operations after closing the transaction.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The TI MMIC business accounted for less than $40 million in 1996 revenues, or roughly 2% of the $1.8 billion in total TI defense revenues, and was sold to TriQuint Semiconductor, Inc.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Raytheon retained its own existing MMIC capabilities and has the right to license TI's MMIC technology for use in future product applications from TriQuint.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Shortly after Raytheon acquired TI DSEG, Raytheon then acquired Hughes Aircraft from General Motors.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Raytheon then owned TI's mercury cadmium telluride detector business and infrared (IR) systems group.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In California, it also had Hughes infrared detectors and an IR systems business.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] When the US government again forced Raytheon to divest a duplicate capability, the company kept the TI IR systems business and the Hughes detector business.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] As a result of these acquisitions, these former arch-rivals of TI systems and Hughes detectors work together.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Immediately after acquisition, DSEG was known as Raytheon TI Systems (RTIS).
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] It is now fully integrated into Raytheon, and this designation no longer exists.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI was active in the area of artificial intelligence in the 1980s.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In addition to ongoing developments in speech and signal processing and recognition, it developed and sold the Explorer computer family of Lisp machines.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] For the Explorer, a special 32-bit Lisp microprocessor was developed, which was used in the Explorer II and the TI MicroExplorer (a Lisp Machine on a NuBus board for the Apple Macintosh).
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI was a major original-equipment manufacturer of sensor, control, protection, and RFID products for the automotive, appliance, aircraft, and other industries.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The Sensors & Controls division was headquartered in Attleboro, Massachusetts.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] By the mid-1980s, industrial computers known as PLC's (programmable logic controllers) were separated from Sensors & Controls as the Industrial Systems Division, which was sold in the early 1990s to Siemens.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 2006, Bain Capital LLC, a private equity firm, purchased the Sensors & Controls division for $3.0 billion in cash.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The RFID portion of the division remained part of TI, transferring to the Application Specific Products business unit of the Semiconductor division, with the newly formed independent company based in Attleboro taking the name Sensata Technologies.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1997, TI sold its software division, along with its main products such as the CA Gen, to Sterling Software, which is now part of Computer Associates.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] However, TI still owns small pieces of software, such as the software for calculators such as the TI InterActive!.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI also creates a significant amount of target software for its digital signal processors, along with host-based tools for creating DSP applications.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] For the fiscal year 2017, Texas Instruments reported earnings of $3.682 billion, with an annual revenue of $14.961 billion, an increase of 11.9% over the previous fiscal cycle.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI shares traded at over $82 per share, and its market capitalization was valued at over $88.0 billion in October 2018.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] As of 2018, TI ranked 192nd on the Fortune 500 list of the largest United States corporations by revenue.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] As of 2016, TI is made up of four divisions: analog products, embedded processors, digital light processing, and educational technology.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] As of January 2021, the industrial market accounts for 41 percent of TI's annual revenue, and the automotive market accounts for 21 percent.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI's remaining businesses consisting of DLP products (primarily used in projectors to create high-definition images), calculators and certain custom semiconductors known as application-specific integrated circuits.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Texas Instruments sells DLP technology for TVs, video projectors, and digital cinema.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The ASICs business develops more complex integrated-circuit solutions for clients on a custom basis.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI has produced educational toys for children, including the Little Professor in 1976 and Dataman in 1977.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI produces a range of calculators, with the TI-30 being one of the most popular early calculators.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI has also developed a line of graphing calculators, the first being the TI-81, and most popular being the TI-83 Plus (with the TI-84 Plus being an updated equivalent).
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Many TI calculators are still sold without graphing capabilities.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The TI-30 has been replaced by the TI-30X IIS.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Also, some financial calculators are for sale on the TI website.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 2007, TI released the TI-Nspire family of calculators and computer software that has similar capabilities to the calculators.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Less than 3% of Texas Instruments’ overall revenue comes from calculators, part of the $1.43 billion revenue in the "Other" section in the company's 2018 annual report.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Nevertheless, the calculators are a lucrative product.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] For example, estimates have a $15 to $20 cost to produce TI-84 Plus which likely has a profit margin of at least 50%.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Throughout the 1980s, Texas Instruments worked closely with National Council of Teachers of Mathematics (NCTM) to develop a calculator to become the educational standard.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In 1986, Connecticut School Board became the first to require a graphing calculator on state-mandated exams.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Chicago Public Schools gave a free calculator to every student, beginning in the fourth grade, in 1988.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] New York required the calculator in 1992 for its Regents exams after first allowing it the previous year.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The College Board required calculators on the Advanced Placement tests in 1993 and allowed calculators on the SAT a year later.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Texas Instruments provides free services to the College Board, which administers AP tests and the SAT, and also has a group called Teachers Teaching for Technology (T3), which educates teachers on how to use its calculators.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In the 1990s, with the advent of TI's graphing calculator series, programming became popular among some students.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The TI-8x series of calculators (beginning with the TI-81) came with a built-in BASIC interpreter, through which simple programs could be created.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The TI-83 was the first in the series to receive native assembly.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Around the same time that these programs were first being written, programmers began creating websites to host their work, along with tutorials and other calculator-relevant information.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] This led to the formation of TI calculator webrings and eventually a few large communities, including ticalc.org.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The TI community reached the height of its popularity in the early 2000s, with many new websites and programming groups being started.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] In fact, the aforementioned community sites were exploding with activity, with close to 100 programs being uploaded daily by users of the sites.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Also, a competition existed between both sites to be the top site in the community, which helped increase interest and activity in the community.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] One of the common unifying forces that has united the community over the years has been the rather contentious relationship with TI regarding control over its graphing calculators.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI graphing calculators generally fall into two distinct groups—the older ones powered by the Zilog Z80 and the newer ones running on the Motorola 68000 series.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] Both lines of calculators are locked by TI with checks in the hardware and through the signing of software to disable use of custom operating systems.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] However, users discovered the keys and published them in 2009.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI responded by sending invalid DMCA takedown notices, causing the Texas Instruments signing key controversy.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI has the largest market share in the analog semiconductor industry, accounting for over $10 billion of the total $57 billion market in 2020.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] On April 4, 2011, Texas Instruments announced that it had agreed to buy National Semiconductor for $6.5 billion in cash.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] TI paid $25 per share of National Semiconductor stock, which was an 80% premium over the share price of $14.07 as of April 4, 2011, close.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The deal made TI the world's largest maker of analog technology components.
[src:ti-rtos/texas-instruments] The companies formally merged on September 23, 2011.
